Using  metal  amides  to  transform  a  relatively  inert  C-H  bond  into  a  more  reactive  C-M  bond  selectively  is  a  key  strategy  in  organic  synthesis.1,2  For  this  purpose,  hindered  lithium  amides,  such  as  lithium  diisopropylamide  (LDA)  and  lithium  2,2,6,6- tetramethylpiperidide  (LiTMP),  are  very  useful  bases  that  allow  several  aliphatic  and  aromatic  substrates  to  be  regioselectively  deprotonated.2  However,  the  high  ionic  character  of  the  C-Li  bond may preclude organolithium reagents from being applied in  substrates  bearing  important  functional  groups,  like  ester  and  cyano.   Over  the  last  years,  magnesium  amides,  first  reported  by  Hauser in 1947,3 have emerged as relevant alternatives to lithium  amides because the corresponding magnesium Grignard reagents  display  superior  thermal  stability  and  higher  tolerance  to  the  presence of sensitive functional groups.4 In 1989, Eaton reported  that  directed  ortho-magnesiations  of  aromatic  substrates  like  methyl  benzoate  could  be  conducted  at  room  temperature  by  using  Hauser  bases.5  Mulzer6  and  Kondo7  further  expanded  the  scope  of  to  functionalized  heterocyclic  substrates including pyridines, thiazoles, and indoles. Moreover,  in  chiral  magnesium  amides  can  be  potentially  applied  enantioselective deprotonation reactions.8   Tetrahedron  j o u r n a l   h o m e p a g e :   w w w . e l s e v i e r . c o m

Magnesium-  and  zinc-TMP  amides  have  come  out  from  relative  obscurity  to  be  recognized  as  important tools in modern synthetic chemistry. Development of LiCl-activated metal amides like TMPMgCl·LiCl  and  TMP2Zn·2MgCl2·2LiCl  has  been  important to  obtain  new  organometallic  reagents  through  highly  chemo-  and  regioselective  reactions.  Herein,  we  review  how  these  reagents are applied in the synthesis of important bioactive targets such as natural products and  drugs.   Despite  the  potential  applications  of  Hauser  bases  in  organic  synthesis,  these  compounds  tend  to  aggregate  and  hence  be  poorly  soluble  in  commonly  used  ethereal  solvents.  Therefore,  large  excess  of  the  magnesium  amide  may  be  necessary  to  achieve  full  metalation.  Knochel  and  co-workers  circumvented  this  problem  by  developing  LiCl-activated  TMP  bases.  The  mixed Li/Mg amides TMPMgCl·LiCl (1)9 and TMP2MgCl·2LiCl  (2)10  proved  to  be  more  soluble  and  reactive  reagents  and  were  able to promote highly selective magnesiation in the presence of  stoichiometric  amounts  of  the  base.  Reagents  1  and  2  have  complementary  reactivities;  amide  TMPMgCl·LiCl  is  largely  used  for  magnesiation  of  reactive  heterocyclic  substrates,  while  diamide  TMP2MgCl·2LiCl  is  normally  applied  to  magnesiate  moderately  activated  substrates  such  as  tert-butyl  benzoate  (Figure 1).9,10

In  addition,  the  Li/Zn  amides  TMP2Zn·2MgCl2·2LiCl  (3)11  and TMPZnCl·LiCl (4)12 may provide selective zincation at room  temperature or even under heating (including microwave heating)  in  very  sensitive  aromatic  substrates  in  the  presence  of  reactive  functional  groups  (Figure  1).11,12  Extensive  investigations  into  these mixed metal amides have shown their wide applicability in  the chemo- and regioselective metalation of numerous arenes and  heteroarenes.13 Furthermore, since both magnesium and zinc have  two empty low-lying p-orbitals, they can be transmetalated with  transition  metals  (e.g.,  palladium,  copper, or  nickel),  leading   to  2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved. various electrophiles.14  To bring this exciting class of reagents to attention, we aim to  present  a  brief  review  of  the  recent  applications  of  magnesium-  and zinc-TMP amides in the synthesis of bioactive targets, such  as natural products and drugs.  2. Synthetic applications of magnesium-TMP amides

The  pyrimidine  scaffold  exists  in  the  structure  of  relevant  bioactive  compounds.  In  2008,  Mosrin  and  Knochel  studied  pyrimidine  magnesiation  with  TMPMgCl·LiCl.18  They  also  employed  this  strategy  to  prepare    inhibitors  of  protein  kinase  p38  and  phospholipase  sPLA2,  which  are  antiviral  and  anti- inflammatory  In  both  syntheses,  4,6-dichloro-2- (methylthio)pyrimidine  (10)  was  used  as  starting  material.  Interestingly,  although  lithiation  of  10  with  LDA  had  been  reported  at  -78  °C for  3  h,20  magnesiation  with  TMPMgCl·LiCl  took  place  at  room  temperature  within  20  min.  Transmetalation  of  organomagnesium  reagent  11  with  CuCN·2LiCl  followed  by  acylation  with  2-chlorobenzoyl  chloride  gave  ketone  12  in  90%  yield.  Subsequent  cyclization  with  NH2NH2·H2O  provided  the  p38  kinase  inhibitor  13  in  79%  yield.  On  the  other  hand,  iodolysis  of  11  followed  by  amination  at  position  6  with  benzylamine  furnished  pyrimidine  14  in  82%  yield  (two  steps).  After  a  Sonogashira  cross-coupling  with  1-butyne,  t-BuOK- mediated  cyclization  of  the  corresponding  amino-substituted  aryl-alkyne gave phospholipase sPLA2 inhibitor 15 in reasonable  yield (Scheme 2).

Direct lithiation of pyrimidines is known to be difficult due to  high  reactivity  of  the  ring  toward  addition  of  organolithium  reagents.21 In this context, magnesiation appears as an interesting  option.  In  2009,  Mosrin  and  Knochel22  used  the  base  TMPMgCl·LiCl  in  two  sequential  steps  to  obtain  the  fungicide  mepanipyrim.23  Regioselective  di-functionalization  of  2- chloropyrimidine  (16)  in  the  presence  of  iodine  and  1,2- dibromotetrachloroethane  as  electrophiles  afforded  4-bromo-2- chloro-6-iodopyrimidine  (18)  in  87%  overall  yield. Pd(dba)2 (3 mol%) P(o-furyl)3 (6 mol%) CuI (4 mol%), Et3N propyne (2 equiv), 25 °C, 1.5 h, 97% In  2003,  Fusetani’s  group  isolated  five  new  alkaloids  (dictyodendrins  A-E)  from  the  marine  sponge  Dictyodendrilla  verongiformis  (Figure  2).  This  new  class  of  marine  alkaloids  displayed  noteworthy  inhibitory  activity  against  telomerase,  an  enzyme  found  to  be  normally  expressed  in  90%  of  human  malignant tumors.27

Remarkably,  in  2011  Tokuyama  and  co-workers  reported  on  the  synthesis  of  all  five  alkaloids  by  using  a  highly  substituted  indole  (30)  as  a  common  intermediate.28  To  synthesize  the  indoline precursor 29 from substrate 27, the magnesium diamide  TMP2Mg·2LiBr29  was  more  efficient  than  TMPLi  and  other  hindered  bases  in  the  planned  benzyne  generation-cyclization  sequence.  In  this  context,  a  relevant  limitation  of  the  use  of  TMPLi  as  a  base  was  formation  of  a  TMP  adduct  with  rising  temperature.    In  contrast,  reaction  of  27  with  TMP2Mg·2LiBr  allowed  effective  preparation  of  magnesiated  indoline  2.  Moreover,  transmetalation  of  this  intermediate  with  CuI  was  crucial for arylation to occur in high yield (Scheme 5).   Figure 2. Dictyodendrins A-E (26a-e).  Tokuyama  group  also  employed  the  indoline  synthesis  strategy  to  prepare  important  pyranoindoles,30  which  have  potential  activity  against  hepatitis  C  virus  (HCV).31  A  benzyne- mediated  cyclization  was  this  case  performed  by  in  TMP2Mg·2LiCl  followed  by  the  corresponding  organocopper  intermediate  methylation  with  iodomethane  provided  the  key  indoline 32 in 80% yield (Scheme 6). These results indicate that  there  is  no  significant  difference  in  using  TMP2Mg·2LiBr  or  TMP2Mg·2LiCl bases in these reactions, since both indolines 29  and 32 were obtained in similar yields when 5 equivalents of the  corresponding reagentes were used.

In  2011,  Wipf  and  co-workers  described  the  synthesis  and  biological  evaluation  of  novel  benzothienothiazepinone  analogues  that  can  inhibit  protein  kinase  D.32  The  authors  synthesized  a  promising  lead  structure  named  kmg-NB4-23  (40)  from  methyl  3-aminothiophene-2-carboxylate  (37)  in  seven  steps.  Notably,  selective  magnesiation  of  38  with  TMPMgCl·LiCl  at  C-6  followed  by  quenching  with  methyl  cyanoformate  allowed  the  methyl  ester  derivative  39  to  be  isolated in 97% yield. To build the thiazepinone moiety, a one- pot bromide displacement-condensation of 39 with cysteamine  hydrochloride was performed, which afforded 40 in 68% yield  (Scheme 7).

In  2004,  Singh  and  co-workers  isolated  three  new  11- membered  unsaturated  lactones  from  Aspergillus  sp.  Among  these  molecules,  aspercyclides  A  inhibited  immunoglobulin  E  (IgE)  binding  to  receptors  with  an  IC50  of  200  µM.33  Recently,  Sato and co-workers achieved total synthesis of aspercyclides A  and B when they used an interesting intramolecular oxidative C- O  bond  formation  in  the  key  step.34  Interestingly,  the  authors  obtained  two  important  synthetic  intermediates  of  the  natural  products from dioxinone 42, which they had readily prepared in  83%  yield  through  ortho-metalation  of  dioxinone  41  with  TMP2Mg·2LiCl  as  selective  base  and  iodine  as  electrophile  (Scheme 8).   A  Mizoroki-Heck  reaction  of  iodide  44  with  alkene  45  furnished 46 in 66% yield. Reaction of alcohol 46 with dioxinone  43  gave  ester  47  in  88%  yield,  which  was  further  converted  to  Aspercyclides A and B after several synthetic steps (Scheme 9).  Scheme 8. In  this  case,  a  limitation  to  the  use  of  lithium  bases  would be low tolerance of organolithium reagents to the presence  of  ethyl  ester  groups.  Notably,  reactions  of  49  with  TMPMgCl·LiCl followed by quenching of the organomagnesium  intermediates with aldehyde 50 afforded the expected alcohols of  type  51  in  60-70%  yields.  Subsequent  reduction  of  nitro  and  hydroxyl  groups,  lactamization,  N-alkylation,  and  deprotection  produced  the  desired  tricyclics  lactams  of  type  53  in  reasonable  isolated yields (Scheme 10).  invertebrates,  especially  sponges  and  ascidians,  are  often  brightly  colored  due  to  the  presence  of  pyridoacridine  alkaloids.38  In  2014,  Bracher  and  co-workers  synthesized  named  demethyldeoxyamphimedine (60),39 which was isolated from the  marine ascidian Cystodytes dellechiajei in 2011.40    The  synthetic  route  started  with  frustrated  Lewis  pairs  TMPMgCl·BF3·LiCl  in  the  selective  functionalization  of  ethyl  In  2011,  discovery  of  various  novel  non-ATP

This  reagent,  easily  prepared  by  mixing  the  base  TMPMgCl·LiCl  with  BF3·OEt2,  can  perfom  regioselective  C-4 functionalization of pyridines bearing functional groups at C- 3.41  After  transmetalation  with  ZnCl2,  a  palladium-catalyzed  Negishi  cross-coupling  of  55  with  2-iodoaniline  (56)  formed  a  biaryl intermediate, which provided product 57 in 50% yield after  intramolecular  lactamization.  Compound  57  was  then  converted  into  aryl-bromide  by  using  POBr3  and  submitted  to  a  Negishi  cross-coupling with organozinc 55, to generate 59 in 78% yield.  Finally, highly controlled metalation of 59 with TMPMgCl·LiCl  followed  by  intramolecular  cyclization  allowed  the  desired  marine  natural  product  60  to  be  isolated  in  28%  yield  (Scheme  11).   In  2015,  the  same  group  synthesized  various  pyridoacridine  alkaloids  by  a  similar  methodology.42  Suzuki  cross-coupling  reactions  between  4-bromobenzo[c][2,7]naphthyridine  (61)  and  boronic  acids  led  to  four  derivatives  of  type  62  with  yields  ranging  from  73%  to  90%.  Furthermore,  treatment  of  ester  62  with  TMPMgCl·LiCl  followed  by  intramolecular  cyclization  gave  pentacyclic  compounds  63a-d  with  yields  varying  from  27% to 33% (Scheme 12).

More recently, Bracher’s group also developed a new strategy  to  prepare  some  benzylisoquinoline  alkaloids,43  which  were  isolated  from  Menispermum  dauricum  DC  rhizome.44  The  to  metalate  alkoxy  authors  used  TMPMgCl·LiCl  base  isoquinolines 64a-c  regioselectively.  After  attempts  of using  the  Negishi reaction to reach the biaryl derivatives of type 68 failed,  the  authors  quenched  65a-c  with  the  iodoisoquinolines  of  type  66  (53-67%  yields),  which  they  then  readily  converted  into  68a-c  (65-77%  yields)  by  Suzuki  cross- couplings  in  the  presence  of  boronic  acid  pinacol  ester  67.  Further  acid-catalyzed  ester  hydrolysis  followed  by  cyclization  with Eaton’s reagent allowed 6-O-demethylmenisporphine (69a),  Scheme 12. Recently,  the  search  for  new  non-nutritive  sweeteners  has  attracted  much  attention.  In  this  context,  Noncovich  and  co- workers  employed  the  hT1R2/hT1R3  cell-based  assay  to  screen  various  commercially  available  natural  products.45  Among  these  compounds,  NP-011694  (76)  presented  high  potential  for  such  purpose,  so  the  authors  investigated  its  total  synthesis.  To  achieve a brominated building block 73, the authors initiated the  synthesis by carrying out selective magnesiation of compound 70  with  1,2- dibromotetrachloroethane, product 71 was obtained in 97% yield.  This result illustrated the superior tolerance of organomagnesium  reagents  to  the  presence  of  functional  groups  in  aromatic  substrates.  Subsequently,  a  set  of  deprotection,  protection,  and  reduction  reactions  provided  intermediate  73.  After  a  bromine- lithium exchange reaction of 73 with n-BuLi, the  corresponding  organolithium derivative was reacted with aldehyde 74 and then  treated  with  tetrabutylammonium  fluoride  to  afford  75  in  70%  yield over two steps, which was then converted into NP-011694  in three steps (Scheme 14).  dauriporphinoline  (69b),  and  bianfugecine  (69c)  to  be  isolated  Scheme 13. In  2003,  Fusetani  and  co-workers  isolated  four  active  compounds  from  marine  the  Didemnum  proliferum  species,  including  enediyne  compound  shishijimicin  A,  which  exhibited  highly  potent  antitumor  properties.46  Nicolaou and co-workers then performed the first total synthesis  of this molecule.47 In a convergent synthesis, the authors obtained  the  building  block  78  by  metalating  carboline  77  with  mixed  followed  by  lithium/magnesium  quenching with I2. Lithium-iodide exchange with t-BuLi allowed  coupling  with  disaccharide  aldehyde  79  with  86%  yield.  Shishijimicin  A  (81)  was  then  obtained  after  several  steps  (Scheme 15).  In  2016,  Knochel’s  group  demonstrated  the  applicability  of  mixed  lithium/magnesium  amides  to  prepare  marine  alkaloid  rigidin A (88),48 which has potent calmodulin antagonistic action;  2,4-dimethoxypirimidine  (82)  was  used  as  starting  material.49  Although  lithiation  of  82  with  LiTMP  at  0  °C  has  been  reported,50  the  use  of  TMPMgCl·LiCl  as  a  base  and  iodine  as  electrophile  allowed  sequential  double  functionalization  of  the  substrate to give the diiodo derivative 83 in 65% isolated yield. After  copper-catalyzed  amination  of  83,  deprotonation  of  the  resulting  pyrimidyl  N-sulfonylamide  84  with  KHMDS  and  triflate  reaction  with  phenyl((trimethylsilyl)ethynyl)iodonium  afforded  the  corresponding  N-alkynylation  product  85  in  67%  yield.  Remarkably,  following  the  I-Mg  exchange  promoted  by  the  turbo  Grignard  reagent,  the  organomagnesium  intermediate  was  transmetalated  with  CuCN·LiCl,  to  afford  pyrrolo[2,3- d]pyrimidine  87  in  57%  yield  after  carbocupration  reaction  and  benzoylation  with  86.  Rigidin  synthesis  was  completed  after  Suzuki  arylation  at  C-3  and  N-sulfonylamide  and  methoxy  groups cleavage (Scheme 16).

In  1996,  Matsumoto  and  co-workers  isolated  the  potent  antibiotic  agent  lactonamycin  from  Streptomyces  rishiriensis.51  Seven  years  lactonamycin  Z  from  Streptomyces sanglieri,52 and this agent also presented antitumor  activity. One of the greatest challenges regarding the preparation  of  this  kind  of  compound  is  related  to  a  pentacyclic  core.53  Recently,  Parsons  and  co-workers  developed  a  new  approach to  synthesize the core of this important class of compounds through  a  free-transition-metal  cyclization  strategy.54  Aiming  at  the  synthesis  of  alcohols  of  type  91,  first  the  authors  investigated  addition  of  diyne  89a  to  aldehyde  90  in  the  presence  of  ZnBr2.  However,  under  these  conditions,  the  zincated  alkyne  did  not  emerge,  and  a  naphthalene derivative  of  90  was  isolated  as  sole  product.  In  contrast,  the  corresponding  magnesium  acetylides  were  easily  generated  by  reactions  between  alkynes  89a-b  and  TMPMgCl·LiCl  to  give  alcohols  91a-b  in  60%  and  55%  yield,  respectively.  Lastly,  thermal  cyclization  in  medium  containing  toluene  and 1,2-epoxyhexane  furnished  products 92a  (73%)  and  92b (88%) in good yields (Scheme 17).   Scheme 16. Synthesis of alkaloid 88.

Recently, Zhang and co-workers synthesized enone 96, which  is  an  important  precursor  for  tetracycline  antibiotics,55  by  metalation of isoxazole ring 93 in the key step.56 First, the group  screened for metalation conditions by means of lithium reagents  n-BuLi,  n-hexyllithium,  and  LiTMP.  However,  very  low  temperatures  were  required,  and  sub-optimal  results  were  obtained,  with  allylic  metalation  competing  for  the  isoxazole  deprotonation.  Such  issues  were  alleviated  with  the  use  of  TMPMgCl·LiCl. After reacting with furaldehyde 94, the authors  obtained  carbinols  95a-b  in  95%  yield  (95a/95b  (3.5:1)).  Interestingly, this reaction was successfully performed on a large  scale (281.6 mol) (Scheme 18).  3. Synthetic applications of zinc-TMP amides

In  2013,  Carrera  et  al.  synthesized  a  lead  compound  that  inhibited PI3Kδ activity.61 Recent studies have pointed to the key  role  of  this  specific  kinase  in  rheumatoid  arthritis  progression,  making  PI3Kδ  a  potential  target  to  treat  this  autoimmune  disease.62 Preparation of one representative compound of known  PI3Kδ  inhibitors,  GNE-026  (106),  was  possible  through  a  TMPZnCl·LiCl-mediated  metalation  step.  After  scanning  for  optimum  metalation/halogenation  protocols,  the  authors  found  that the best condition was to employ TMPZnCl·LiCl to metalate  102, followed by quenching with iodine solution, to give 103 in  86%  yield  on  a  preparative  scale  (140  g).    By  using  TMPZnCl·LiCl,  the  authors  also  overcame  low  reactivity  issues  when purine substrate of type 102 reacted with bases like n-BuLi,  LDA, and TMPMgCl·LiCl in the presence of ZnCl2. Thereafter,  etherification  with  N-Boc-azetidinol  (104),  Boc  group  deprotection  with  HCl,  and  reductive  amination  with  1,1- dioxothian-4-one  and  sodium  triacetoxyborohydride  provided  GNE-293 (106) in 41% overall yield (Scheme 20). α,β-Difunctionalized  cyclic  ketones  are  relevant  building  blocks  in  organic  synthesis,  but  their  preparation  often  depends  on  multistep  approaches  starting  from  enones.71  Recently,  Newhouse and co-workers developed a versatile one-pot strategy  for  α,β-difunctionalization  of  saturated  cyclic  ketones.72  In  the  first  step  of  this  process,  a  zinc  enolate  was  generated  by  using  Zn(TMP)2,  since  the  lithium  bases  TMPLi  and  LiCyan  were  inefficient.  Next,  the  zinc  enolate  was  oxidized  with  an  allyl- palladium catalyst, to produce an enone intermediate (127). This  was  telescoped  with  an  organocuprate  reagent,  which  allows  conjugated  addition  of  a  nucleophile  at  β-position,  forming  an  enolate that could be trapped with an electrophile and giving the  α,β-difunctionalized  ketones  (128).  This  methodology  was  crucial for the synthesis of some precursors of biologically active  compounds  such  as  (-)-hibiscone  C  (130a),  cyclobakuchiol  B  (130b),  and  11-Nor-∆8-THC  methyl  ester  (130c),  which  was  achieved  in  better  yields  as  compared  to  previous  multistep  reports (Scheme 25).73   Scheme 24 Synthesis of thieno-fused 7 deazapurine ribonucleosides (125).   3-iodothiophene, Pd(PPh3)4, THF, 65°C, 16 h (0.55 equiv), THF, 0°C for 60 min then r.t. for 45 min 1,4-dibromobenzene, 180 °C, 30 min) UV (254 nm, 4W) TFA, rt, 3 days

Summary and conclusion  Over the last years, the development of new synthetic methods  has increased the scope of applications of magnesium- and zinc- TMP  amides  considerably.  These  reagents  are  extremely  important  in  modern  synthetic  chemistry,  as  demonstrated  through  the  synthesis  of  several  natural  products  and  pharmacologically  relevant  targets.  TMPMgCl·LiCl  is  the  most  frequently  used  mixed  Li/Mg  amide  base;  it  can  be  applied  to  prepare  highly  functionalized  aromatic  and  heteroaromatic  synthetic  intermediates.  On  the  other  hand,  mixed  Li/Mg  diamides such as TMP2Mg·2LiCl can be employed to metalate of  less activated substrates.  Since  the  first  reports  on  their  preparation  and  reactivity  in  2007,  TMP2ZnCl·2MgCl2·2LiCl  and  TMPZnCl·LiCl  have  become  an  exciting  addition  to  the  organic  synthesis  toolset  available  to  chemists.  Aiming  to  synthesize  bioactive  targets,  synthetic  chemists  have  successfully  used  these  reagents  to  metalate sensitive heterocyclic substrates.

Alongside  reports  on  the  use  of  LiCl-activated  magnesium-  and  zinc-TMP  amides  on  large-scale  building  block  batch  preparations,  recent  publications  have  also  illustrated  the  great  potential  of  these  reagents  in  flow  chemistry.74  These  new  developments will greatly impact the future use of these reagents  in organic synthesis. Giuliano  Cesar  Clososki  was  born  in  1974  in  Capitão  Leônidas  Marques-PR,  Brazil.  He  completed  his  undergraduate  studies  (1999)  and got his Master degree (2000) at  the  Federal  University  of  Paraná  (Brazil)  under  the  supervision  of  Prof. Fabio Simonelli. He spent one  year at the University of California  working  with  Prof.  Bruce  H.  Lipshutz (2003) and got his Ph.D degree at the University of São  Paulo (2005) under the supervision of Prof. João V. Comasseto.  After working one year with Prof. José A. R. Rodrigues (Brazil)  and  two  years  with  Prof.  P.  Knochel  (Germany)  as  postdoctoral  researcher,  in  2008  he  accepted  the  position  of  Assistant  Professor  at  the  Faculty  of  Pharmaceutical  Sciences  of  Ribeirão  Preto – University of São Paulo, where he is now an Associated  Professor.  His  actual  research  interests  include  the  development  of  new  synthetic  methods  and  the  synthesis  of  bioactive  molecules for pharmaceutical applications.   Rodolfo  Hideki  Vicente  Nishimura  studied  chemistry  at  the  University of São Paulo (2007 - 2012). He obtained his M.Sc. in  Organic  Chemistry  (2015)  under  the  supervision  of  Giuliano  Cesar  Clososki  (2015).
